http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value:
The Building Performance Ontology (BOP) is a set of ontological constructs which allows integration of data related to building performance. By (re-)using ontology patterns from major ontologies in the field, BOP provides a method to integrate both static and dynamic (time-series) properties to buildings, zones, elements and products. 

It's aim is to facilitate building managers and facility managers with a common data structure to ease the process of data integration and to allow software tools to deal with the large heterogeneity of data. 

By (re-)using concepts from major ontologies in the field, BOP could easily be integrated with a wide range of existing ontologies and datasets. BOP could be seen as an extension of existing work rather than an individual ontology.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: An act of carrying out an actuation procedure by an actuator to change the state of a property.
An agent that can implement an actuation procedure to change the state of a property..
A collection of documents in a database.
The most recently defined state of a property.

A collection of data.

The database class is used to describe an external database, storing results of executions, such as a time-series database.
An act of carrying out a procedure by an executor on a property
Het doen of uitvoeren van iets. Een uitvoering kan worden uitgevoerd door een uitvoerder, eventueel op basis van een procedure.
An agent that can implement a procedure to perform an execution.
Iets wat een taak kan uitvoeren op basis van een procedure.
An abstraction of a real-world phenomenon which could be described in terms of its properties.
Een abstractie van een fenomeen uit de echte wereld (object, onderdeel, zone, evenement, etc).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: An object, part, zone, event etc.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: A function of a feature of interest.
An act of carrying out an observation procedure by a sensor to observe the state of a property.
An entity that hosts an executor.
A measurable and intrinsic characteristic of a feature of interest.
Een kenmerk van een feature of interest. Het kenmerk is intrinsiek aan en kan niet bestaan zonder de feature of interest.
A collection of properties. The collection could also be a singleton or a null set.
Een collectie van eigenschappen. De collectie kan ook een eenpuntsverzameling of een lege verzameling zijn.
The outcome of an execution.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: The result may hold, for example, a value, a unit, a result time and other provenance data.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: An agent that can implement an observation procedure to measure the state of a property.
A particular quantity value that has been chosen as a scale for measuring other quantities of the same kind.
Een specifieke waarde van een natuurkundige grootheid die is gekozen als een schaal voor het meten van andere hoeveelheden van diezelfde grootheid.
Linking a property with a result

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value:
This object property is used to directly link a property to a property state. 

Example: Temperature -- hasPropertyState --> CurrentTemperatureState

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Linking a feature of interest with a simple property value described as a literal.
Linking a property with a simple property state value described as a literal.
Linking an execution with a simple result value described as a literal.
Linking a result with a unit described by a literal.
The simple value of a result.
Linking a property with the executor which acts on this property.
Linking a collection with the database it is part of.
Linking a result with a feature of interest

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value:
This object property is used to directly link the current state of a property to a feature of interest. It is the shortest route to link a result to a feature of interest. 

Example: CurrentWallLength --isComplexPropertyOf --> Wall

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Linking a result with a property

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value:
This object property is used to directly link the current state of a property to a property. It is the shortest route to link a result to a property. 

Example: CurrentTemperatureState -- isPropertyStateOf --> Temperature

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Linking a result with an execution.
Relation between an actuator and sub-actuators. The sub-actuators are of type actuator and could function as individual actuators.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: The object property could be used to model actuators which have multiple components with their own functions.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Relation between an executor and sub-executors. The sub-executors are of type executor and could function as individual executors.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: The object property could be used to model devices which have multiple components with their own functions. A multisensor - for example - consists of multiple sub-sensors which individually perform a sensing function.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Relation between a sensor and sub-sensors. The sub-sensors are of type sensor and could function as individual sensors.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#exam.@value: The object property could be used to model sensors which have multiple components with their own functions.
